Popular Farms and Mills Ltd, a company that allegedly forcefully held its works and stopped them from leaving company premises throughout the lockdown over COVID-19 has denied the allegations leveled against it by human rights group and the police. In a statement signed by the administrative manager of the company, Mr Saka Kareem and made available to journalists in Kano yesterday  described the allegations as baseless and unfounded and an attempt by its detractors to tarnish its image. According to the statement at no time did the company force any of its workers to stay in the premises during the period in question against his or her will. ” In fact all of the workers were given free hand to move freely only for some of them who willingly chose to stay at the premises for fear of being affected by the COVID 19 and were magnanimously accommodated inside the company,” the statement said. The statement  further revealed that ” all workers living within the premises were provided with toiletries, Five Hundred Naira daily as feeding allowances, and monthly appreciation bonuses in addition to the contractual payments without any delay.